nodes.title: Source Mode
widgets_values:
#1 for Img2Vid (Image Mode)
#2 for Vid2Vid (Video Mode)

If you get the "size of tensor" mismatch error in Video Mode, try adjusting the GDINO threshold, resizing the source, or change the prompt. It's an unfortunate bug where the GDINO mask loses tracking and doesn't create the right amount of frames with the others.

You can check which colored mask isn't tracking properly by looking at the frames in the "Preview Image Debug" node at the bottom of each masking group, or the mask video in your "ComfyUI/Temp" folder. It will be the one that is shorter.

Update: This has been fixed by merging the masks that fail to track with the background layer, up to the same batch as the others.

This workflow allows you to segment up to 8 different elements from an input image, or video, into colored masks for IPA to stylize and animate each element with.

First, select your source input mode in the middle with the switch. 1 is Image Mode, 2 is Video Mode.

At the top of each colored layer is a GDINO-SAM node and a prompt field to type in which element to isolate from your input. The BLACK layer at the end is your background and anything that isn't masked, it should always be enabled. The prompt fields are filled with some basic examples, but you can change them into whatever you want related to your input, like objects, landscape stuff, or even colors. 

You can increase the threshold under the prompt to affect how strong it tries to isolate the keyword. Lower threshold is weaker and will mask bleed into other things, too high and it won't mask anything. A good spot is around 0.30.

On the "GrowMaskWithBlur" node, you can customize the mask using the expand and blur radius settings.

The prompt conditionings beside each "Load Image For IPA" node are more for soft-tuning and don't have a very strong effect.

Colored mask layers not being used should be bypassed with the "Fast Groups Bypasser" node. You can also bypass the "Input Gen" so you can fine-tune your masks before going into the ksampler.

There are HRFix upscaling groups as well. HRFix_NNLatent is similar to HRFix, but creates a softer image, and can be turned to the SDXL version for a difference in color and detail.

The ControlNet weights can be adjusted to control how delineated the IPA stylization is. Less weight on the CNs will give more freedom to the masks and retain less of the input edges. More weight will produce more of the input structure, but less quality on the stylization, it's a balancing act of your choosing.

linktr.ee/ArtOnTap
Disable colored groups not being used, RED and BLACK always need to be enabled. To save time, disable the "Input Gen" group to fine-tune your masks before piping to the KSampler.
